<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910719-0043</DOCNO><DOCID>910719-0043.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Lafarge Corp.:   Slowdown, Strike Contribute   To 87% Decline in Earnings</HL><DATE>07/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   F.LAF LAF</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>BUILDING MATERIALS, CONCRETE, GLASS, PAINT (BLD)EARNINGS (ERN)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>EUROPE (EU)FRANCE (FR)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)VIRGINIA (VA)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   Lafarge Corp., suffering from the slowdown in theconstruction industry and a strike at one of its cementplants, said second-quarter earnings plunged 87%.   Net income fell to $4.3 million, or eight cents a share,from $32.5 million or 58 cents a share, a year earlier. Salesfell 11% to $428.5 million. The 1990 results reflect theacquisitions of two cement companies and related assets.</LP><TEXT>   In the first six months, the Reston, Va., company reporteda loss of $74.8 million, or $1.34 a share, compared with ayear-earlier loss of $17.5 million, or 32 cents a share.   Robert W. Murdoch, president, said Lafarge's focus for therest of the year would be on improving short-termproductivity and consolidating numerous acquisitions.   Lafarge is majority-owned by France's Lafarge Coppee S.A.,a major producer of building materials.</TEXT></DOC>